1
00:00:04,360 --> 00:00:06,220
Stanford University.

2
00:00:08,200 --> 00:00:09,420
All right,

3
00:00:09,420 --> 00:00:14,740
so last quarter we studied classical mechanics.

4
00:00:15,080 --> 00:00:18,840
And classical mechanics is fairly intuitive.

5
00:00:19,820 --> 00:00:24,300
The basic ideas are things that you can visualize.

6
00:00:25,140 --> 00:00:28,420
You can picture in your head motion of particles,

7
00:00:28,420 --> 00:00:29,660
motion of objects.

8
00:00:30,120 --> 00:00:33,330
It gets a little hard when you start

9
00:00:33,330 --> 00:00:36,540
thinking of ten particles all at the same time.

10
00:00:38,040 --> 00:00:39,360
But nevertheless,

11
00:00:39,360 --> 00:00:44,320
the whole thing is based on

12
00:00:46,620 --> 00:00:50,680
concepts that are drawn from pretty much the everyday world.

13
00:00:51,040 --> 00:00:51,880
Of course,

14
00:00:51,880 --> 00:00:54,020
it gets more and more abstract as you go along.

15
00:00:54,300 --> 00:00:55,720
The crazy French,

16
00:00:55,720 --> 00:00:57,520
who were obsessed with elegance,

17
00:00:57,520 --> 00:00:58,970
kept making it more and

18
00:00:58,970 --> 00:01:00,420
more and more mathematically elegant.

19
00:01:03,300 --> 00:01:03,940
Lagrangians,

20
00:01:03,940 --> 00:01:05,000
Poisson brackets,

21
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:06,600
blah blah blah.

22
00:01:07,340 --> 00:01:09,680
Turned out all to be tremendously important.

23
00:01:13,560 --> 00:01:14,840
The abstractions,

24
00:01:14,840 --> 00:01:15,000
though,

25
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:17,220
are not all that difficult to understand.

26
00:01:17,500 --> 00:01:22,980
And the basic concept is the concept of updating.

27
00:01:23,400 --> 00:01:23,880
Well,

28
00:01:24,300 --> 00:01:24,820
before that,

29
00:01:24,820 --> 00:01:27,060
the concept of a space of states.

30
00:01:27,800 --> 00:01:29,160
What is the state of a system?

31
00:01:29,360 --> 00:01:30,680
Even before that,

32
00:01:30,680 --> 00:01:32,480
the concept of a system.

33
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:34,120
A closed,

34
00:01:34,120 --> 00:01:37,820
isolated system that doesn't interact with anything,

35
00:01:38,660 --> 00:01:41,440
and whose motion and whose evolution,

36
00:01:41,440 --> 00:01:42,700
whose history,

37
00:01:42,700 --> 00:01:44,140
you wish to predict.

38
00:01:44,800 --> 00:01:46,600
Classical mechanics is predictive.

39
00:01:49,499 --> 00:01:50,860
It's deterministic.

40
00:01:54,440 --> 00:01:55,860
And the first concept,

41
00:01:55,860 --> 00:01:56,640
as I said,

42
00:01:56,640 --> 00:01:58,680
after the concept of a system,

43
00:01:58,680 --> 00:02:01,640
is the concept of the state of a system.

44
00:02:02,580 --> 00:02:05,180
Systems can have a collection of different states.

45
00:02:05,420 --> 00:02:08,650
We talked about some very simple examples

46
00:02:08,650 --> 00:02:11,880
the first day of the quarter last time.

47
00:02:13,019 --> 00:02:15,759
I just described for you the most

48
00:02:15,759 --> 00:02:18,500
elementary simple systems consisting of nothing more,

49
00:02:18,580 --> 00:02:19,080
for example,

50
00:02:19,080 --> 00:02:19,780
than a coin.

51
00:02:20,620 --> 00:02:21,780
Heads and tails.

52
00:02:22,120 --> 00:02:24,220
The only states of the system.

53
00:02:24,220 --> 00:02:25,380
The only states of the system are heads and tails.

54
00:02:26,580 --> 00:02:28,800
They form a mathematical set.

55
00:02:29,880 --> 00:02:30,800
The states.

56
00:02:31,839 --> 00:02:33,320
Two of them for heads and tails.

57
00:02:33,580 --> 00:02:34,440
Two points.

58
00:02:34,580 --> 00:02:35,300
One space.

59
00:02:36,080 --> 00:02:37,060
Two states.

60
00:02:38,240 --> 00:02:40,500
And we can draw them as dots.

61
00:02:41,800 --> 00:02:43,280
This one stands for heads.

62
00:02:43,400 --> 00:02:44,420
This one stands for tails.

63
00:02:46,460 --> 00:02:48,360
And you know,

64
00:02:48,360 --> 00:02:51,080
it's easy to picture in your head.

65
00:02:54,260 --> 00:02:55,140
From there,

66
00:02:55,140 --> 00:02:58,300
we talked about equations of motion.

67
00:02:59,060 --> 00:03:00,200
Equations of motion,

68
00:03:00,200 --> 00:03:03,660
or laws of evolution for the simple,

69
00:03:03,660 --> 00:03:04,180
very simple,

70
00:03:04,180 --> 00:03:06,300
system of a couple of points,

71
00:03:06,300 --> 00:03:07,780
heads,

72
00:03:07,780 --> 00:03:08,560
tails,

73
00:03:09,240 --> 00:03:11,100
we formulated some very,

74
00:03:11,100 --> 00:03:13,360
very simple possible laws of motion.

75
00:03:13,960 --> 00:03:16,060
The simplest being nothing happens.

76
00:03:16,420 --> 00:03:17,680
If you start with heads,

77
00:03:17,680 --> 00:03:18,700
you stay heads,

78
00:03:18,700 --> 00:03:19,000
heads,

79
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:19,340
heads,

80
00:03:19,340 --> 00:03:19,680
heads,

81
00:03:19,680 --> 00:03:19,880
heads.

82
00:03:20,380 --> 00:03:21,700
If you start with tails.

83
00:03:21,840 --> 00:03:22,640
You stay tails,

84
00:03:22,640 --> 00:03:22,920
tails,

85
00:03:22,920 --> 00:03:23,240
tails,

86
00:03:23,240 --> 00:03:23,560
tails,

87
00:03:23,560 --> 00:03:23,860
tails.

88
00:03:24,100 --> 00:03:24,200
Tails,

89
00:03:24,200 --> 00:03:24,200
tails,

90
00:03:24,200 --> 00:03:24,200
tails.

91
00:03:25,140 --> 00:03:27,440
that was a very simple law of motion

92
00:03:28,480 --> 00:03:30,460
more complicated law of motion

93
00:03:31,280 --> 00:03:34,520
if you begin with heads you go to tails

94
00:03:34,520 --> 00:03:36,420
if you begin with tails you go to heads

95
00:03:36,420 --> 00:03:39,380
and just oscillate back and forth

96
00:03:40,900 --> 00:03:44,380
the basic idea is the idea of updating

97
00:03:45,220 --> 00:03:47,320
if you know everything there is to know

98
00:03:47,320 --> 00:03:49,420
about a system at an instant of time

99
00:03:49,420 --> 00:03:52,490
then classical mechanic everything that

100
00:03:52,490 --> 00:03:55,560
there is to know essentially means

101
00:03:55,560 --> 00:03:59,000
everything that's needed in order to predict the future

102
00:03:59,839 --> 00:04:02,240
if you know everything that needs to be known

103
00:04:02,820 --> 00:04:05,540
then classical mechanics consists of a set of equations

104
00:04:06,180 --> 00:04:09,020
which tells you how to update the state

105
00:04:09,020 --> 00:04:12,000
given its value at any given time

106
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,280
how to go from one time to the next

107
00:04:16,599 --> 00:04:19,100
that basic idea for example

108
00:04:21,120 --> 00:04:22,650
well I don't think I

109
00:04:22,650 --> 00:04:24,180
need to describe the examples again

110
00:04:24,180 --> 00:04:26,000
we described them at length last time

111
00:04:29,460 --> 00:04:31,580
and that's extremely intuitive

112
00:04:32,420 --> 00:04:35,680
in going from these very simple discrete examples

113
00:04:36,400 --> 00:04:38,740
to a world of continuous motion

114
00:04:39,420 --> 00:04:40,960
indeed we have to abstract

115
00:04:40,960 --> 00:04:42,990
we have to replace the idea

116
00:04:42,990 --> 00:04:45,020
of a small number of states

117
00:04:45,020 --> 00:04:47,160
a small finite number of configurations

118
00:04:47,920 --> 00:04:49,400
by an infinite number of states

119
00:04:49,420 --> 00:04:53,680
for example the motion of a particle along a line

120
00:04:54,599 --> 00:04:56,919
we have to label the states

121
00:04:56,919 --> 00:04:59,240
by the points along a line

122
00:04:59,240 --> 00:05:00,860
as well as their velocities

123
00:05:01,420 --> 00:05:03,260
and so it does get more complicated

124
00:05:03,260 --> 00:05:07,580
but nevertheless classical physics consists of equations

125
00:05:07,580 --> 00:05:09,450
which tell you how to update

126
00:05:09,450 --> 00:05:11,320
the state at any given time

127
00:05:11,320 --> 00:05:13,340
and it's completely deterministic

128
00:05:14,820 --> 00:05:17,140
and as I said easy to visualize

129
00:05:17,140 --> 00:05:19,400
or at least by comparison easy to visualize

130
00:05:19,400 --> 00:05:22,920
because it makes use of concepts from the ordinary world

131
00:05:22,920 --> 00:05:26,020
which your brain is rather hardwired

132
00:05:26,020 --> 00:05:28,260
to be able to understand

133
00:05:29,039 --> 00:05:31,700
now I always give a little sermon at this point

134
00:05:32,219 --> 00:05:33,680
and I'm going to give it again

135
00:05:33,680 --> 00:05:35,720
probably you've heard it a dozen times

136
00:05:39,499 --> 00:05:44,100
about the way one has to think about physics

137
00:05:44,100 --> 00:05:45,960
beyond classical physics

138
00:05:45,960 --> 00:05:47,960
when you move past classical physics

139
00:05:47,960 --> 00:05:50,280
I don't think it can be said enough

140
00:05:50,280 --> 00:05:51,860
and it's so rarely said

141
00:05:51,860 --> 00:05:53,760
that I think I will say it again

142
00:05:54,719 --> 00:05:59,260
and it's that once physics moves past the realm

143
00:05:59,750 --> 00:06:04,160
of parameters that has to do with ordinary experience

144
00:06:06,860 --> 00:06:09,260
either objects which are so small

145
00:06:09,260 --> 00:06:12,300
that they're far beyond what ordinary physics is about

146
00:06:12,960 --> 00:06:15,140
or velocities which are so fast

147
00:06:15,140 --> 00:06:17,460
that they're far beyond ordinary velocities

148
00:06:17,460 --> 00:06:21,760
whenever we move out of the range of parameters

149
00:06:21,760 --> 00:06:24,240
that we're familiar with from ordinary experience

150
00:06:26,080 --> 00:06:31,080
we inevitably run into things that we cannot visualize

151
00:06:32,920 --> 00:06:36,420
nobody can visualize the motion of an electron

152
00:06:37,460 --> 00:06:39,600
it's just not wired for it

153
00:06:40,409 --> 00:06:44,080
nobody can visualize four dimensional space

154
00:06:44,080 --> 00:06:46,480
or four dimensional space time

155
00:06:48,580 --> 00:06:52,380
let alone ten or eleven dimensions

156
00:06:55,120 --> 00:06:57,900
it's not the way physics is done

157
00:06:57,900 --> 00:07:00,430
I often read some of the

158
00:07:00,430 --> 00:07:02,960
stuff that goes back and forth

159
00:07:02,960 --> 00:07:04,280
between some people

160
00:07:04,280 --> 00:07:06,500
I suspect people in this class

161
00:07:07,300 --> 00:07:10,160
about trying to explain to themselves

162
00:07:10,160 --> 00:07:11,000
to each other

163
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:13,100
or to ask questions of each other

164
00:07:13,100 --> 00:07:17,360
about certain abstract physical questions

165
00:07:17,460 --> 00:07:19,290
and I notice very much

166
00:07:19,290 --> 00:07:21,120
that a lot of the mistakes

167
00:07:21,120 --> 00:07:22,360
a lot of the confusion

168
00:07:23,460 --> 00:07:27,700
happens because of trying to visualize things

169
00:07:27,700 --> 00:07:33,200
using the old fashioned or standard intuitions

170
00:07:33,200 --> 00:07:34,920
that you're hardwired for

171
00:07:36,180 --> 00:07:38,980
you may think that physicists

172
00:07:38,980 --> 00:07:41,660
good physicists are especially good

173
00:07:41,660 --> 00:07:43,660
at visualizing these things

174
00:07:43,660 --> 00:07:44,520
they're not

175
00:07:44,520 --> 00:07:46,260
I cannot visualize five,

176
00:07:46,260 --> 00:07:46,540
six,

177
00:07:46,540 --> 00:07:47,160
seven dimensions

178
00:07:47,160 --> 00:07:48,540
any better than you can

179
00:07:50,420 --> 00:07:53,560
but I know how to use abstract mathematics

180
00:07:54,400 --> 00:07:55,420
to describe it

181
00:07:56,400 --> 00:07:57,900
there's no substitute

182
00:07:57,900 --> 00:07:59,620
there really is no substitute

183
00:07:59,620 --> 00:08:03,160
for the process of abstracting

184
00:08:03,160 --> 00:08:04,720
and using mathematics

185
00:08:04,720 --> 00:08:07,780
to describe the things which are beyond your ability

186
00:08:07,780 --> 00:08:09,480
to directly visualize

187
00:08:10,200 --> 00:08:12,000
the example that I always give

188
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:13,780
and I'm going to do it again tonight

189
00:08:14,520 --> 00:08:15,560
I'm going to really focus on it

190
00:08:15,560 --> 00:08:17,590
and realize that you're not

191
00:08:17,590 --> 00:08:19,620
going to understand quantum mechanics

192
00:08:19,620 --> 00:08:21,640
by trying to visualize it as some

193
00:08:21,640 --> 00:08:23,880
funny form of classical mechanics

194
00:08:23,880 --> 00:08:24,460
it won't work

195
00:08:24,460 --> 00:08:25,480
you'll always get it wrong

196
00:08:26,900 --> 00:08:30,380
but just the idea of visualizing

197
00:08:31,380 --> 00:08:34,700
space of dimensions different than three dimensions

198
00:08:35,520 --> 00:08:37,580
in particular I always used to say

199
00:08:37,580 --> 00:08:37,919
okay,

200
00:08:37,919 --> 00:08:40,780
how many people here can visualize five dimensions

201
00:08:41,429 --> 00:08:43,120
and everybody would say

202
00:08:43,120 --> 00:08:43,659
no,

203
00:08:43,659 --> 00:08:44,480
we can't

204
00:08:44,480 --> 00:08:45,680
of course there were a few fakers

205
00:08:45,680 --> 00:08:48,260
a few clowns in the class

206
00:08:48,260 --> 00:08:49,260
who would say,

207
00:08:49,260 --> 00:08:49,400
yeah,

208
00:08:49,400 --> 00:08:49,860
I can do it,

209
00:08:49,860 --> 00:08:50,340
I can do it

210
00:08:50,340 --> 00:08:50,840
but they couldn't

211
00:08:50,840 --> 00:08:51,700
and they knew they couldn't

212
00:08:51,700 --> 00:08:53,820
they can't visualize five dimensions

213
00:08:57,140 --> 00:08:59,460
but then I began to realize also

214
00:09:00,140 --> 00:09:01,420
you've probably heard this before

215
00:09:02,420 --> 00:09:04,020
that it's equally hard

216
00:09:04,020 --> 00:09:06,600
to directly visualize two dimensions

217
00:09:07,240 --> 00:09:08,600
and so I would say to the class

218
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:08,860
okay,

219
00:09:08,860 --> 00:09:10,820
how many people now can visualize two dimensions

220
00:09:10,820 --> 00:09:12,840
and almost everybody would raise their hands

221
00:09:13,960 --> 00:09:15,920
and I would say

222
00:09:15,920 --> 00:09:16,640
no,

223
00:09:16,640 --> 00:09:17,620
you're wrong

224
00:09:17,620 --> 00:09:19,020
close your eyes,

225
00:09:19,020 --> 00:09:20,440
try to visualize two dimensions

226
00:09:20,440 --> 00:09:21,180
and they would,

227
00:09:21,180 --> 00:09:21,440
they'd say,

228
00:09:21,440 --> 00:09:21,740
okay,

229
00:09:21,740 --> 00:09:22,380
I see it

230
00:09:22,380 --> 00:09:24,480
I see two-dimensional curved space

231
00:09:25,840 --> 00:09:28,680
what they're seeing is not two-dimensional curved space

232
00:09:28,680 --> 00:09:31,080
what they're seeing is a two-dimensional surface

233
00:09:31,080 --> 00:09:32,980
embedded in three dimensions

234
00:09:34,060 --> 00:09:36,300
even try to see one-dimensional space

235
00:09:36,300 --> 00:09:37,500
one-dimensional abstract,

236
00:09:37,500 --> 00:09:38,820
one-dimensional space

237
00:09:38,820 --> 00:09:40,020
is just a line

238
00:09:40,020 --> 00:09:42,920
you cannot see that line in your head

239
00:09:43,120 --> 00:09:46,220
without seeing it as a line drawn in a plane

240
00:09:46,220 --> 00:09:48,820
and the plane you can't see without seeing it

241
00:09:48,820 --> 00:09:50,180
as embedded in three dimensions

242
00:09:50,180 --> 00:09:51,000
what's going on?

243
00:09:51,160 --> 00:09:51,840
why can't you?

244
00:09:52,320 --> 00:09:53,600
I hate to tell you this

245
00:09:53,600 --> 00:09:55,800
but you're prisoners of your own neural architecture

246
00:09:56,620 --> 00:09:59,800
your neural architecture was built for three dimensions

247
00:10:00,880 --> 00:10:01,400
alright,

248
00:10:01,400 --> 00:10:02,560
how do you get around it?

249
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:03,520
well,

250
00:10:03,520 --> 00:10:06,140
you don't get around it by training yourself

251
00:10:06,140 --> 00:10:07,880
to see four or five,

252
00:10:07,880 --> 00:10:08,620
six dimensions

253
00:10:09,340 --> 00:10:11,420
you get around it by training yourself

254
00:10:11,420 --> 00:10:13,000
to think abstractly about it

255
00:10:14,020 --> 00:10:14,640
okay,

256
00:10:14,640 --> 00:10:18,020
if three-dimensional space is a point x,

257
00:10:18,020 --> 00:10:18,460
y,

258
00:10:18,460 --> 00:10:18,900
and z

259
00:10:18,900 --> 00:10:21,740
then four-dimensional space is x,

260
00:10:21,740 --> 00:10:22,180
y,

261
00:10:22,180 --> 00:10:22,460
z,

262
00:10:22,460 --> 00:10:22,940
and w

263
00:10:22,940 --> 00:10:25,540
and you learn to manipulate the symbols

264
00:10:25,970 --> 00:10:28,400
now that's not to say that after a while

265
00:10:28,400 --> 00:10:30,260
you don't start to gain a

266
00:10:30,260 --> 00:10:32,120
new kind of intuition for things

267
00:10:32,120 --> 00:10:32,960
you do

268
00:10:32,960 --> 00:10:36,440
but the intuition is not the process of

269
00:10:37,939 --> 00:10:40,540
physical visualization of the same kind

270
00:10:40,540 --> 00:10:43,100
as when you visualize a plane

271
00:10:43,120 --> 00:10:45,180
or a wave as a wave in the ocean

272
00:10:50,959 --> 00:10:53,900
so I warn you about that

273
00:10:53,900 --> 00:10:56,720
and I will tell you quantum mechanics

274
00:10:56,720 --> 00:10:59,540
is about as abstract as anything can be

275
00:11:01,660 --> 00:11:02,380
well,

276
00:11:02,380 --> 00:11:06,000
perhaps things are even getting a little more abstract now

277
00:11:07,060 --> 00:11:07,600
but again,

278
00:11:07,600 --> 00:11:10,880
quantum mechanics is about things that

279
00:11:10,880 --> 00:11:15,040
your evolutionarily developed neural structure

280
00:11:15,040 --> 00:11:17,780
is not prepared to deal with directly

281
00:11:17,780 --> 00:11:19,420
how do you deal with it?

282
00:11:19,500 --> 00:11:21,140
abstract mathematics again

283
00:11:23,439 --> 00:11:24,880
and relativity,

284
00:11:24,880 --> 00:11:26,560
it's also true of relativity

285
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:28,840
it's worse than quantum mechanics

286
00:11:30,300 --> 00:11:31,020
okay,

287
00:11:31,020 --> 00:11:31,560
let's uh

288
00:11:35,660 --> 00:11:36,760
let's begin

289
00:11:40,880 --> 00:11:43,500
with quantum mechanics at the very very

290
00:11:43,500 --> 00:11:46,120
simplest most primitive question you can ask

291
00:11:47,500 --> 00:11:49,200
what is the state

292
00:11:49,200 --> 00:11:49,400
well,

293
00:11:49,400 --> 00:11:51,460
